9th Ebola epidemic outbreak in DRC in the Equateur region. Bikoro and Mbandaka city affected this is the hub for regional exchanges in proximity to CAR and Republic of Congo. A week after this was declared over DRC were confronted with a 10th outbreak in North Kivu Province. On 1 August 2018 the Ministry of Health of the Democratic Republic of the Congo notified WHO of a new outbreak of Ebola virus disease (EVD) in North Kivu Province in the eastern part of the country. The province of North Kivu is among the most populated provinces with eight million inhabitants. It shares borders with four other provinces (Ituri South Kivu Maniema and Tshopo) as well as with Uganda and Rwanda. (There is a tangible risk of EVD transmission in Uganda and Rwanda). The sub-region has been experiencing intense insecurity and worsening humanitarian crisis with over one million internally displaced people and a continuous efflux of refugees to the neighbouring countries including Uganda Burundi and Tanzania. The protracted conflict context makes the emergency response activities more difficult because of restrained access and security risks. The EVD outbreak is rapidly evolving with more new confirmed cases and deaths occurring. WHO regional risk raised to HIGH. Category of emergency (IFRC): RED

An eighteen month programme through the IFRC to initiate A Journey Towards PRCS Digitalisation . The project will be using the latest digital technology solutions to push the PRCS systems to become more effective transparent and accountable - enabling to follow the money the people and the outcomes while leaving no one behind . It is envisaged that the project interventions would be instrumental to have a bigger faster and more cost-effective impact on the lives of poor people we as a movement target in Pakistan. It will improve Governance and accountability to reach more beneficiaries in cost effective manners. First phase will be the stratigic assessment and planning process and then phases 2 & 3 its roll out first at HQ level and then across the provincial branches.

After more than three years the conflict in Yemen that has brought about a man-made humanitarian disaster affecting 22.5 million people. As a result of the protracted violence thousands of civilians have been killed or injured and millions displaced. Widespread damage to public infrastructure and severe shortage of supplies owing to restrictions on the movement of goods into and within the country make it nearly impossible for the majority of Yemenis to obtain food water medical care and other essentials. A cholera outbreak occurred in May 2017 although the number of suspected cases has been declining in the past few months. Nevertheless people remain vulnerable to contracting communicable diseases. Attacks against humanitarian actors hinder the delivery of aid. Since March 2015 seven Yemen Red Crescent Society volunteers and two ICRC staff members have been killed while carrying out their duties. The few international organizations present in the country struggle to respond to the outstanding needs of victims. Killing of ICRC staff member 21st April 2018 outside Taiz. ICRC are currently evacuating all mobile staff from Taiz and have suspended activities and movements across Yemen. At this point it is premature to determine the impact of this appalling incident on our operations in the country however the ICRC remains committed to its humanitarian endeavour and to keep responding to the dire humanitarian needs in Yemen.
Agreement between ZRCS and BRC for the support of Organisational Development and Disaster Management in line with ZRCS strategic plan and Election Preparedness Plan 2017-18

A national state of emergency was declared by the Government of Namibia in May 2013 requesting international assistance for an estimated 331 000 people in rural communities classified as food insecure (14% of the total population). Another 450 000 were classed as moderately food insecure and the results of an Inter-Agency Emergency Food Security Assessment indicated that upcoming agricultural production will be poor and exacerbate these issues due to the lowest seasonal rainfall for decades. The Namibia Red Cross Society (NRCS) launched an appeal to intervene in four of the worst affected regions.

After a fivefold increase in normal rainfall from January to March 2017 Peru is experiencing flooding. This is most severe in the North Western coastal region and department of Lima. The Peruvian government has declared a state of emergency in affected zones in 12 departments and has declared sanitation emergency in 11 departments. Infrastructure has been widely damaged including health centres schools and bridges and roads making transport of humanitarian aid difficult. Meteorological experts have predicted that that the coastal el Niño will extend to at least April 2017.

An estimated 201 800were affected by heavy rainfall and flooding. 98% of the 70 000 displaced are in Asunción. Most affected areas include Alto Paraguay Presidente Hayes (Bajo Chaco) Asunción and Ñeembucú. This ten-month emergency operation led by the Paraguayan Red Cross enabled the National Society to provide 2 765 people with psychosocial support; 7 030 people with basic hygiene promotion activities and information; 2 685 families who were located in collective centres were provided with hygiene kits kitchen kits tarpaulins and toolkits to cover and protect the roofs and walls of their shelters. The PRC also provided 386 families with buckets water dispensing bags and jerry cans from the standard Federation Kit 2 for water and sanitation disaster response. Additionally another 1 998 families received supplies for the transport and storage of safe water consumption (buckets and water filters). A total of 345 families received supplies for water treatment (water purification supplies and tablets for water treatment). The Paraguayan Red Cross also distributed food kits to 1 370 families.

A packed train derailed on the route that links Yaoundé and Douala on Friday 21 st October killing at least 60 people and injuring more than 600. Cameroon RC deployed 25 volunteers on the spot (3 local 12 from Yaoundé and 10 from Douala) and was the only humanitarian non-governmental actor on the ground in support to authorities search and rescue efforts. The IFRC is in the process of drafting a DREF to support Cameroon s Red Cross response operations. British Red Cross has received an unsolicited donation of 25 000 from GSK (GlaxoSmithKline is a British pharmaceutical company) which will be used to make a contribution to the IFRC DREF.

6 February 2019 government declared a measles outbreak. Since January 2019 there have been 16 349 cases of measles reported with 261 deaths. Almost every region of the Philippines has been affected the most vulnerable are young children (1-2 years old). 12 February 2019 IFRC activated a 5 month DREF for CHF 181 417 to support PRC in two main ways: providing vaccinations to 60 000 children and a nationwide education campaign on the importance of getting vaccinated. 6 March 2019 Emergency Appeal (CHF 2m) launched to supported the vaccination of a further 200 000 children and one million to be reached with health information. Appeal to run from April - September 2019.
